Anonymous Wed 08 Jul 2020 05:51:10 No.31371850 Report
Quoted By: >>31371879 >>31382171
Corsac foxes (also known as steppe foxes or simply corsacs) are a fox species native to steppes and semi-deserts in Central Asia. Their habitat stretches from Kazakhstan to Manchuria, and reaches as low as Afghanistan. The closest related species to the corsac fox is the Tibetan sand fox.

They are smaller than the red fox, but have slightly larger legs and ears. They are excellent climbers (thanks to their hooked claws), but are slow runners. Their coat becomes thicker in the winter. They have great eyesight, hearing, and smell. They lack the extreme odor that other foxes have. The bark when hunting or when alerting rivals, and they use high-pitched yelps and chirps as alarm calls and social greetings.

They are built for arid climates and as such, they need little water to survive, as they obtain most of the needed moisture from their food. They are primarily carnivorous, and they mostly eat small to medium-sized animals and insects. They also scavenge for carrion, and sometimes eat fruits and vegetables. Their prey is often buried in cashes. One source claims that they can survive without food for extended periods of time, but they may have mistaken food for water, as they go on to talk about them getting their needed moisture from food.

They are nocturnal, although they are diurnal in captivity. They do not have territory, and will sometimes form packs. They cannot hunt in deep snow, and as such, migrate closer to the south during the winter. They shelter in burrows, oftentimes stolen from another animal. The dens they dig are often shallow. Dens are often shared in a social pack, they have several entrances. They form hunting packs in the winter, which mostly includes the mating pair and their offspring.

Mating season stretches from January to March. The males fight for the females and succeeding males form monogamous pairings with the female. They create a den to raise their young, which is sometimes shared with other pregnant females, but they move dens several times. The losing males are not exiled from the pack. They typically have 2-6 young, but can have as many as 10 kits in a single litter. Kits are born blind and open their eyes at 2 weeks. I have read a few articles and I haven’t found any source that claims they are promiscuous. I wouldn’t bring that up if this general didn’t emphasize monogamy so much.

They are very vulnerable to poaching, and they’re often hunted for their pelts. They are also heavily affected by natural disasters. Despite the frequent poaching and natural disasters fluctuating their population numbers, their population has proved resilient, as they are listed as least concern on the IUCN Red List. A few sources claim that their numbers are on the decline.

Before you go too deep, decide how you want to handle the outside environment. Sync up the landscape to the tech level. If it's handled unrealistically you have an animesque setting that operates on rule of cool. A touch more realistic, and you get a Mad Max (and I mean the 80s versions) free for all.
If things are just mildly uncomfortable in the short term but debilitating the longer you stay outside, that's one setting.
If the acid raid is so bad that protection is needed no matter how low the exposure, that's another.

That's a tricky aspect to it. There's some context to the setting that would be missing within the framing of this particular story, and on this particular planet. The reader of this wouldn't really know that this is basically a pulp fantasy version of the solar system where the sun is a deity that purged itself of the hindrance of flesh and blood, and the empty space between planets has air you can breathe and pressure doesn't apply/exist and depending on distance to sun you won't freeze to death. There is something resembling magic in the setting but there's a sharp divide between most living things and the creatures capable of using it, and it's irrelevant for the most part on the world of Fifthborn (Not-Jupiter) which is the most technology driven world of the system.

At best with minimal storms overhead the air is tainted with miasma, limiting oxygen intake and causing suffocation or lethal damage to lungs in about fifteen minutes. When the storms are raging you'd last a minute at best and every second you'd wish it took one second. Holes punched into hulls must be plugged up quick before miasma and caustic burns disables the driver. The storms never truly stop and are constantly chipping away at the surface, and maintaining equipment and barriers/filters for shelter is a constant struggle.

So yeah it might be "animesque" in the sense that it doesn't obey rules of nature as we know them, and within the context of the story would seem grounded enough that it should. If that makes sense.

As a writer, there's two things.

First, the technical. Grammar, spelling, and all the objective bits.

Second, and this is something I used with beta/first readers (and have when i do that for other writers) is a worksheet.
Rather than drop a 500 word paragraph on the writer, it breaks things down for them and let's the reviewer focus on a chunk at a time.

The object is not to have a CYOA, but to break out the lexical sandpaper.

Sci-Fi always chased public ignorance

>30's and 40's superheroes came from strange chemicals as industrial chemistry produced all new materials

>50's and 60's heroes and villains were nuclear or came from fallout

>70's, 80's, 90's pollution caused lots of "toxic waste" characters, genetics and medicine resulted in "mutants" everywhere

>90's & 2000's internet and tech based characters. lots of nano-tech stuff inspired by microprocessor manufacturing,

>2000's 2010's quantum bullshit in full swing. particle physics parlance enters public consciousness causing lots of multiverse stories.

The best sci-fi usually serves as counter examples, which helps to make them timeless. By not chasing trends it seems less quaint in retrospect. That's why the original Star Trek works, they didn't explain the science behind teleporters or warp speed. It didn't work with the current science nor was it derived from it so it never became "wrong". It was just a setting with its own rules.
